node.text: women are sexualized from the moment they are children. they don’t even understand the meaning of sexy and already they’re hearing comments about their bodies. we’re taught that our bodies and how much we show of them define our worth. we’re taught to hate the widening of our hips, and our growing chests. we’re taught to cover up so we don’t tempt others. but why aren’t others taught to control themselves? to ask for consent? teach kids it is normal for their bodies to bloom and that they don’t need to be ashamed and cover up if they don’t want to. let them learn and understand consent. teach them adults should know it is wrong to sexualize a child, and they need to speak up if it happens. teach young people to learn to love their bodies and that their worth is not defined by how much of their skin is showing, nor what they are wearing.

April is sexual assault awareness month.  One thing a lot of people don’t realize is that it’s not about sex, it’s about power and control over the victim. What you’re wearing, how you’re acting, the “vibes” you’re giving off, none of that matters. It’s not your fault, it’s theirs for thinking it is okay to violate your body. 
Don’t let them silence you, reach out to someone you trust, whether it’s a friend or a family member, even a member of law enforcement. Don’t let them take away your power. You’re not alone in this
